The figures cf Priapus were generally busts like the Hermae, but sometimes they were full length of the kind Horace describes. Usually they held a sickle or a club in their right hand by way of frightening thieves, and a wisp of straw, or something of that sort, to frighten the birds. Priapus also symbolized the fertility of nature in the later mythology of the Greeks as well as the Romans.
